### Steps to reproduce

1. Run code sample on the iOS simulator or physical iPhone on iOS 16.0+ where the system context menu is supported.
2. Tap anywhere.
3. Tap again on the collapsed selection to reveal the context menu.
4. Tap on "Select All".

### Expected results

Tapping "Select All" selects all the text and reveals the selection handles.

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/ab93e63d-b3b9-4519-8736-e2a31dcf852d

### Actual results

Tapping "Select All" selects all the text but does not reveal the selection handles.

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b7fa54ea-3e83-4716-8400-7dfaa5a57dfa

### What is happening

Using the system context menu on iOS we do not get any signals that we pressed a button in the context menu. That update comes through `EditableTextState.updateEditingValue`, and in that case we hit this line which classifies the cause of the update to be the keyboard https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/0cf1d34e9b7614bb99f1b645d0ad84af69915fb1/packages/flutter/lib/src/widgets/editable_text.dart#L3472.

When this happens we hit the following case which prevents the selection handles from being shown.

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/cd3b0a5a865e3b7b13fdd49da8178ebcdcadcee1/packages/flutter/lib/src/material/text_field.dart#L1349-L1351

### Potential solution

Use a custom button for "Select All" and other buttons that would reveal selection handles with a callback that calls `editableTextState.selectAll(SelectionChangedCause.toolbar)` and similar methods. The "paste" button doesn't reveal selection handles so we can still get secure paste functionality by using the default button.

